rdshire, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Pembridge","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of Family Names in Britain and Ireland © University of the West of England 2016","meanings":["English: locative name from Pembridge (Herefs), which is recorded as  <i>Penebrug(g)e</i> from the 11th to 14th centuries. The place-name derives from an Old English personal name * <i>Pena</i> + Old English  <i>brycg</i> ‘bridge’. In some cases the surname may be from Pen Bridge in Shipley (Sussex), which derives from an uncertain first element + Old English  <i>brycg</i>."],"variants":[{"name":"Pember","meanings":["English: perhaps a variant of <b>Pamber</b>, a habitational name from a place in Hampshire named Pamber, from Old English <i>penn</i> ‘fold, enclosure’ + <i>beorg</i> ‘hill’."]}]},{"name":"Petronella","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Italian Rocco, Fedele, Francesco, Marco, Salvatore, Vito.","Italian (southern): from <i>Petronella</i>, a feminine pet form of   Petrone   or   Petronio  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Petrone","meanings":["From Latin <i>Petronilla</i>, originally a feminine diminutive of the Roman family name <i>Petronius</i> (of uncertain derivation). The name <i>Petronilla</i> was borne by a 1st-century martyr, and early in the Christian era came to be connected with   Peter  , so that in many legends surrounding her she is described as a companion or even the daughter of  St Peter ."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"Lady Petronella Pembridge was born about 1283, in Pandy, Monmouthshire, Wales. She married Richard Pembridge about 1299, in Pandy, Monmouthshire, Wales. They were the parents of at least 2 sons and 2 daughters. She died in 1348, at the age of 66."},"et":{"about 1283–1348":"umbes 1283–1348","1282–1346":"1282–1346","1300–1375":"1300–1375","1312–1385":"1312–1385","1314–Male":"1314–Surnud","1330–Female":"1330–Surnud","1283–1348":"1283–1348","about 1283":"umbe